ce:section.ce:para:
Transmission electron microscopy is a powerful means of observing the morphology of CDs. TEM images (Fig. 1
                        ) exhibit that two typical CDs-25 and CDs-150 are quasi-spherical nanoparticles uniformly dispersed in the B2O3 matrix. And their HR-TEM images present a distinct crystal structure with lattice stripe spacing of 0.21 nm, corresponding to the (100)-crystalline surface of graphite. The particle sizes of CDs-25 and CDs-150 are uniform, ranging from 1.5-4.5 nm, and their average particle sizes are 2.7 and 2.8 nm. There is little significant change in the size of the CDs for the selected two samples. The morphology of the CDs-x composites was also observed with SEM, displaying porous structure (Fig. S4). In the XRD spectra of CDs-10, CDs-25, CDs-70 and CDs-150 (Fig. 2
                        a), a broad characteristic diffraction peak at 2θ = 23.6° indicates the presence of amorphous carbon in the synthesized CDs. Additionally, distinct diffraction peaks at 2θ = 14.5, 28.0 and 39.8° can be observed, which belong to the characteristic peaks of B2O3, providing evidence for the presence of a B2O3 crystal matrix formed by the dehydration of BA during pyrolysis [32,33].
